The High-Reliability Asset Ecosystem
Fusing Rigorous Governance (ORCA) with Human-Centered Behavioral Design
Target Audience: Asset Managers, Operations Directors, and Senior Process Owners • Knowledgebase Core
1. Executive Summary
Traditional asset management models fail because they decouple technical governance from human behavior.
This paper provides a unified architecture that connects the primary financial milestone—Unit Production Cost
(UPC)—directly to front-line data execution.
By layering the Objective-Risk-Control-Assurance (ORCA) methodology on top of a Competency-Based
Attribute System, organizations can eliminate administrative friction. This framework replaces traditional, fear-
driven compliance with an engaging operational environment where front-line workers proactively optimize
processes, protect execution schedules, and verify their own professional mastery.
2. The Operational Engine: Strategic Alignment via ORCA
To drive the asset toward the target performance vector (lowering UPC via optimized OPEX and maximized
production), management must secure the integrity of downstream execution. This is achieved by mapping
the entire operation through a strict ORCA hierarchy.
Lagging Financial Target (UPC) 
   └── Protected by: Production Volume & Outage Window Maintenance
        └── Insulated by: Scope Challenge Controls (Freeze Boundaries)
             └── Driven by: Front-End Notification Data Quality
2.1 The Front-End Strategic Unlock
The single greatest threat to an asset's schedule is late scope break-ins caused by low-quality work
notifications. To protect the execution baseline, every control in the business process must be explicitly
mapped out into an automated, scannable ledger based on a precise system standard:
System Control = Who + What + When + Where + How + Why
By defining exactly who executes a task, where it occurs, and why it protects the business objective, the Asset
Manager creates a completely transparent control network across the entire operation.
